{"add":{"doc":{"id":"8191ca58c8f42ed7ffe54c85f8e6fa88346673a95c5c088611449acc0a9ebfd2","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/63/USA-Hightlighting-Michigan.svg/350px-USA-Hightlighting-Michigan.svg.png","previous":[],"after":["Michigan ( /ˈmɪʃɨgən/ (help·info)) is a Midwestern state of the United States of America. It was named after Lake Michigan, whose name is a French adaptation of the Ojibwe term mishigami, meaning \"large water\" or \"large lake\". Michigan is the eighth most populous state in the United States. It has the longest freshwater shoreline in the world, bounded by four of the five Great Lakes, plus Lake Saint Clair. In 2005, Michigan ranked third for the number of registered recreational boats, behind California and Florida. Michigan has 12,000 inland lakes. A person is never more than six miles (9.7 km) from a natural water source, or more than 85 miles (137 km) from Great Lakes coastline."]}}}